<div id="main_content">
	<h2>Virtual Lines Can Make Waiting More Pleasant, Profitable</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Chad Binette
		
		<span class="date">March 22, 2005</span></p>
	
	
	
		<div class="article_img" style="width: px;">

			<img alt="Article Main Picture" src="../resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/0/NE106/en_US/linemain.jpg" height="" width=""  /> 
			
				<p class="photo_credit">Photo: UCF News file photo</p>
			
			<p>Cutting the time that patrons physically wait for service is one way that businesses and hospitality organizations can improve their reputations and increase customer satisfaction.</p>
			
				<p class="note"><a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=002400413206c3010220adacf2007894">Full Photo</a></p>
			
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
		</div>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:ddickson@mail.ucf.edu">Duncan Dickson</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-903-8042</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:rford@bus.ucf.edu">Robert Ford</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-5088</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:blaval777@aol.com">Bruce Laval</a></h4>
			
			
			
			
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.hospitality.ucf.edu/">Rosen College of Hospitality Management</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.bus.ucf.edu/management/cgi-bin/site/sitew.cgi">Department of Management</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"><font size="3">Waiting in line wastes time you could spend doing something else, like having fun. So, why not let a computer hold your spot?</font></span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> </span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"><font size="3">The Walt Disney Co. adopted that philosophy in 1999, when it installed FASTPASS, a computer system that allowed guests to avoid long lines on five of the Walt Disney World Resorts most popular attractions.</font></span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> </span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span><font size="3"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">Two </span><place /><city /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">University of Central</span></city /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> </span><state /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">Florida</span></state /></place /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> researchers and a retired Disney executive believe other attractions, cruise lines, customer service call-in centers and other businesses could turn to similar systems of virtual lines to make their customers waits more comfortable and to help boost their profits.</span></font></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font size="3"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> </span></font></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font size="3"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span></font><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"><font size="3">Cutting the time that patrons physically wait for service is one way that business, hospitality and service organizations can improve their reputations and increase customer satisfaction, which are critical factors in word-of-mouth advertising, said UCF professors Duncan Dickson and Robert Ford and Bruce Laval, a retired </font></span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"><font size="3">Disney executive.</font></span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"><font size="3"> </font></span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"><font size="3">Virtual lines can take different forms, such as restaurants allowing customers to call ahead from home to claim a spot on a waiting list or customer service centers assigning someone a time to call back and immediately speak with someone instead of keeping them on hold for 45 minutes.</font></span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> </span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"><font size="3">They would be acknowledging that your time is valuable, said Dickson, a professor at UCFs Rosen College of Hospitality Management.</font></span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> </span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span><font size="3"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">In </span><place /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">Central Florida</span></place /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">, virtual lines can help restaurants and other businesses better deal with the long lines that accompany holidays such as Easter and Christmas, large conventions and special events such as the Daytona 500, Bike Week and Spring Break, Dickson said.</span></font></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font size="3"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> </span></font></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font size="3"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span></font><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"><font size="3">Companies need to pay attention both to how long the customer waits for service and how long and enjoyable the wait feels, wrote Dickson; Ford, a professor at the UCF Department of Management; and Laval, retired executive vice president for operations at Disney.</font></span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> </span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"><font size="3">Customers may be more satisfied with longer waits if theyre occupied with hors douevres at restaurants or amusement park television monitors that inform them about the upcoming attractions. Free entertainment also can improve a waiting customers mood, and relaxed customers are more likely than angry, sad or anxious patrons to tolerate longer waits, the researchers wrote.</font></span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> </span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"><font size="3">Businesses also should let customers know how long they should expect to wait and make sure they dont underestimate that time. A customer who waits 55 minutes while anticipating an hour-long wait likely will be more satisfied than one who was uninformed about how long the wait would be.</font></span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> </span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"><font size="3">Even with all of those efforts, however, waits can still be a problem for businesses and their customers, the authors wrote in last months Cornell Hotel and Restaurant Administration Quarterly, a leading hospitality journal. Thats why Disney turned to the FASTPASS system, which is used by more than 50 million guests a year, to assign guests spaces in computer-generated lines.</font></span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> </span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"><font size="3">FASTPASS allows guests to see more attractions in a day because they dont have to wait in as many lines, and the system also has helped Disney increase its profits from concession stands and gift shops because guests have more time to visit them.</font></span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> </span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"><font size="3">Other tourist attractions could benefit from the same approach, and cruise ships could use virtual lines for on-board activities such as skeet shooting or dinner shows. Passengers could try other activities or rest in their cabins instead of waiting in lines.</font></span></p>
		
	
	<p id="back"><a href="index?page=news">&lt; Back to the Newsroom</a></p>

